to use these skills and such, just copy and paste the folders into the .copilot directory 
on your machine and then you are goood

explaination of ai agents, skills, and instcutions for reference:

### Instructions

Always-on rules that govern how the model responds across all tasks.

- Applied automatically to your entire workflow
- Define coding standards and preferences
- Examples: "Always use Python," "Never use library X," "Prefer readable solutions over clever ones"

### Skills

Specialized workflows that load on-demand when a specific task requires them.

- Triggered by the model when relevant to the current task
- Think of them as callable functions the model can use
- Examples: "enhance commit messages," "improve documentation quality"

### Agents

AI entities configured with specific instructions and skills to perform tasks.

- Represents the AI model with a customized rule set (instructions) and capabilities (skills)
- Instructions define what the agent can do; the agent is the executor
- Enable multi-stage workflows with tailored constraints and behavior

i organize my skills but having some acronym or phrase before them
to categorize them so i can know what category they fall
(also copilot ig doesn't allow sub folder of skills in the skills folder :c)

COMS - this skills are for communication
making my messages and emails and such more cleaer
and more focused and tailored to how I want the 
reciever to understand them. (makes writing faster too)

DEVTOOLS - tools that i use during actual development,
not as fleshed out as I want yet, but will be better

DOCS - makes documentation way faster and better
for both myself and others I work with

LRS - learning research studies, basically tools that i use
to learn better and faster, for both personal topics,
for school, and work, really breaks down the learning process
and makes it more efficient and effective and less frustrating
tackling problems and new concepts